snippet.textDisplay: Your boobs getting that big and hard is totally normal. It’s all that mature milk coming in (before youre feeding your baby colostrum) Your body produces a lotttt of milk thats why they feel that way. Your body does not know how much milk your baby will need so thats why it just brings a ton in the beginning. Then after that you start feeding your baby and your milk balances and just makes what your baby needs (in accordance to how much he’s latched on/your pumping) most women do have to hold their boobs with one hand and the baby with the other specially in those first days where the boobs are definitely on the bigger side and the babies are new borns so tiny and small. After your body knows how much you make your boobs do decrease in size. Not to your pre pregnancy size but they are not as big and hard as they were when your mature milk had just come in. Breastfeeding is hard and it’s a whole process. Some woman decided it works for them some don’t and I do not blame you. I am so happy that you did what made YOU happy❤️ Good luck with everything else you decide to do girly❤️

snippet.textDisplay:
I’m a lactation consultant and I agree, a fed baby is best but what I always tell my patients is that once you make it through the first month, the entire experience becomes so much smoother! It’s a learning experience for both mother and baby so it will take time and lots of patience. There are tools and strategies to help latch on a baby while a mom is engorged.

It just breaks my heart (not throwing shade, just what I see all the time) to see moms that have the ability to produce so much milk and choosing not to breastfeed or pump for x or y reason. There are so many moms that dream of breastfeeding and for medical reasons an/or physical/anatomical reasons are absolutely unable to breastfeed their babies. It just happens to go that way. I’m glad you were able to feed him your milk for a little bit, we always say colostrum and breast milk is liquid gold!

Just for future reference, ways that help alleviate the pain of suppressing your milk supply: ibuprofen, drink water only to thirst, use a right sports bra, avoid nipple/breast stimulation, green cabbage leafs and ice packs will help reduce the inflammation. There are also medications that you can take. Those medications are often prescribed to moms that are over producers.

Good luck to all my breastfeeding moms and if you were unable to breastfeed your baby, you’re still the best mom to your baby and he/she loves you the most!

snippet.textDisplay: I would get so many mean opinions from all my family when I told them I wanted to bottle feed my son. My mom even told me that my baby could die and that I didnt love him bc I wouldn't breast feed him. Every woman in my family has breastfed their babies for more than a year so I was the first one not to. It was the most painful experience. I spent so much time and money on stuff that could help me breastfeed and pump. I went to several lactation consultants and tried my hardest even though my nipples were so cracked and bleeding. It was just very painful. My son had a tongue tie so he had to get surgery under his tongue. After that he still struggled to breastfeed and at that point I was done! Seeing him go through pain and hunger pissed me off that I let people's opinions affect my child. Telling a new mom that your child will get sick or that they don't love them bc you don't breast feed was the worst. I didnt let them get to me and continued bottle feeding. He is now 6 years old and I have a 2 year old who I also formula fed and they are both 100% healthy, smart and strong.
